    <section id="introduction">
        <h2>4.0 Introduction</h2>
        <p>Forging equipments are classified according to their principle of operation. The two categories of forging equipment are:</p>
        
        <div class="sector-box">
            <b>(i) Forging hammers:</b> In forging hammers, the forging force is supplied by the falling weight or ram. These are energy restricted machines as deformation results from dissipating the kinetic energy of the ram.
        </div>
        
        <div class="sector-box">
            <b>(ii) Forging presses:</b> Mechanical forging presses are stroke restricted equipment as the length of the stroke and available loads at various positions of stroke represent their capability. Hydraulic presses are load restricted machines as their capability for carrying out forming operation is limited by the maximum load capacity of the press.
        </div>
    </section>

    <section id="hammers">
        <h2>4.1 Forging Hammers or Power Hammers</h2>
        <p>The hammer is the least expensive and most versatile type of equipment for generating load and energy to carry out a forming process. This technology is characterized by multiple impact blows between contoured dies. The hammer is an energy-restricted machine as they get their energy from the potential energy of hammer and on falling of the hammer; this energy is converted into kinetic energy.</p>
        
        <p>During a working stroke, the deformation proceeds until the total kinetic energy is dissipated by plastic deformation of the material when the die faces contact each other. Therefore, it is necessary to rate the capacities of these machines in terms of energy (meter-kilograms or meter-tons). Hammers are primarily used for hot forging, coining, and to enhance metallurgical properties of many materials.</p>

        <h3>4.1.1 Gravity drop hammers</h3>
        <p>Gravity drop hammers have a free falling ram. According to the method for raising the upper ram, they may be classified as board-drop, belt-drop, chain-drop, or piston-lift (oil, air, or steam) drop hammers. The ram is lifted to a certain height and then dropped on the stock placed on the anvil. During the downstroke, the ram is accelerated by gravity and builds up the blow energy.</p>

        <div class="image-container">
            <img src="images/mem/Unit2/Lesson5/2.jpg" alt="Forging drop hammers">
            <p><b>Figure 1: Forging drop hammers</b> (a) Board drop (b) Belt drop (c) Chain drop (d) Power drop</p>
        </div>

        <p>In a gravity-drop hammer, the total blow energy is equal to the kinetic energy of the ram generated solely through free-fall velocity:</p>
        <div class="image-container">
            <img src="images/mem/Unit2/Lesson5/1.jpg" alt="Gravity energy formula">
        </div>

        <h3>4.1.2 Power drop hammers</h3>
        <p>The operation principle is similar to air-drop hammers. In the down stroke, in addition to gravity, the ram is accelerated by steam, cold air, or hot air pressure. In hydraulic gravity power drop hammers, the ram is lifted with oil pressure against an air cushion. The compressed air slows the upstroke and contributes to acceleration during the down stroke.</p>
        
        <p>In a power-drop hammer, the total blow energy is calculated as:</p>
        <div class="image-container">
            <img src="images/mem/Unit2/Lesson5/3.jpg" alt="Power energy formula">
        </div>

        <p>An important feature of any power hammer is that the energy of the blow can be controlled. To minimize vibrations and noise, counter blow hammers use two opposed rams that approach each other. The blow efficiency varies from 0.8 to 0.9 for soft blows and from 0.2 to 0.5 for hard blows.</p>
    </section>

    <section id="presses">
        <h2>4.2 Forging Presses</h2>
        <p>Forging presses are of either mechanical or hydraulic design and are rated on the basis of force developed at the end of the stroke.</p>

        <h3>4.2.1 Mechanical presses</h3>
        <p>Mechanical presses employ flywheel energy transferred to the workpiece by gears, cranks, eccentrics, or levers to translate rotary motion into reciprocating linear motion. The ram stroke is shorter than in a hammer or hydraulic press, making them best suited for low-profile forgings.</p>
        
        <div class="image-container">
            <div style="display:flex; justify-content:center; gap:20px; flex-wrap: wrap;">
                <img src="images/mem/Unit2/Lesson5/4.jpg" alt="Mechanical press type A" style="max-width:45%">
                <img src="images/mem/Unit2/Lesson5/5.jpg" alt="Mechanical press type B" style="max-width:45%">
            </div>
            <p><b>Figure 2: Types of mechanical presses</b></p>
        </div>

        <p><b>Eccentric mechanical presses</b> utilize an eccentric crank. Maximum load is attained when the ram is about 3 mm off the bottom dead centre position. <b>Knuckle joint presses</b> allow very high forces due to linkage design, while <b>screw presses</b> derive energy from a flywheel transmitted through a vertical screw.</p>

        <h3>4.2.2 Hydraulic presses</h3>
        <p>Operation is based on the motion of a hydraulic piston in a cylinder. They are load-restricted machines limited mainly by maximum available load, typically available in capacities from 50 to 1800 tons.</p>

        <div class="image-container">
            <img src="images/mem/Unit2/Lesson5/6.jpg" alt="Hydraulic press">
            <p><b>Figure 3: Hydraulic press</b></p>
        </div>

        <div class="sector-box">
            <b>Important features of hydraulic presses:</b>
            <ul>
                <li>Maximum press load is available at any point during the entire ram stroke.</li>
                <li>Large energies are available for deformation over a long stroke.</li>
                <li>Maximum load can be limited to protect the tooling.</li>
                <li>Ram speed can be varied continuously during the entire stroke cycle.</li>
            </ul>
        </div>
    </section>

